# Cutlass

Open-source **AI-first, prompt-to-edit** video editing (CapCut-inspired): users describe edits; an agent turns that into executable editor commands.

## Stack

- **Slint**: UI layers, timelines, layout, declarative UX.
- **WGPU**: GPU work (preview, compositing/effects/export paths driven from Rust as the engine grows).

## Scope

Ship a **small but real** editor: cut, trim, and other **basic timeline editing**. On top sits an **AI agent** that emits **structured commands**; Rust **executes** those commands against project/timeline state (deterministic edits, auditable undo-friendly actions).

## Timeline semantics (CapCut lane rules)

The model (`cutlass-models::Timeline`) enforces these invariants on every mutation; UI and agent layers rely on them:

- **Main track**: exactly one video lane carries `Track::main` — designated automatically (first video lane added), permanent (delete is refused in the desktop UI and rejected by AI validation; removing it in the model promotes the next video lane), and the default landing spot for the first video dropped on the timeline.
- **Lane zones**: `order` is always partitioned bottom-to-top into audio → main video → other visual lanes (overlay video / sticker / effect / filter / adjustment) → text. Nothing but audio ever sits below the main track; moves/inserts clamp into their zone.
- **Empty lanes**: non-main lanes with no clips are auto-removed (desktop); only the main lane may exist empty.

## Python bindings (side feature)

A **MoviePy-style Python library** (`cutlass-py`) scripts the engine from Python.
This is a **side feature** — the editor, AI agent, and all core stay pure Rust;
Python only wraps the existing renderer and model.

- **Shape**: separate optional crate `cutlass-py` (`crate-type = ["cdylib"]`, PyO3 + `maturin`), depending on `cutlass-engine`/`-compositor`/`-models`. Kept off the default workspace build and shipped to PyPI on its own (`pip install --pre cutlass-py`).
- **API**: track-first v2 wrapper (`Project`, `Track`, `Clip`, `import_media`, `get_frame`, `export`) — do **not** expose the raw `EditCommand` enum to Python. `import_media` probes video, audio, and still images (`kind == "image"`, 5 s default duration). Bundled stickers via `Sticker(asset)` / `cutlass.stickers()`; look animations via `animations()` / `clip.set_animation(slot, id)`.
- **Prerequisite (landed)**: the **timeline → video file exporter** exists — `export_to_file(_observed)` in `cutlass-render` composites every frame and muxes H.264/AAC via `cutlass-encoder` (Apple VideoToolbox and Windows Media Foundation; Linux returns `Unsupported`), wired into the engine, desktop, and mobile.
- **`get_frame(t) -> numpy`**: easy given `RgbaImage` is already `width/height/Vec<u8>`.
- **Composited content**: `CompositeLayer` handles video frames, RGBA bitmaps (text/stills/pen paths/bundled stickers, including animated GIF/APNG/WebP sticker frames), solids, SDF shapes, per-clip masks/chroma and effect/transition chains, per-layer color grades (clip filters/adjustments), canvas-wide lane effect/filter/adjustment passes, and catalog look animations (entrance/exit/combo presets sampled at resolve time).
- **Export audio**: the shared `ExportAudioMixer` varispeed-resamples retimed clips (speed / speed-curve ramps; pitch follows rate for now) and runs RNNoise on denoise-flagged clips; pitch-preserving time-stretch and reversed-clip audio are still deferred.
